   "source": [
    "# removing 8% of unusual outliers (removing less yields outlier-only clusters)\n",
    "\n",
    "iso = IsolationForest(n_estimators=300, contamination=0.08, random_state=RANDOM_STATE, n_jobs=-1)\n",
    "\n",
    "outlier_label = iso.fit_predict(X)\n",
    "outlier_score = iso.decision_function(X)\n",
    "\n",
    "cluster_df[\"outlier_iforest\"] = (outlier_label == -1).astype(int)\n",
    "cluster_df[\"outlier_score\"] = outlier_score\n",
    "cluster_df[\"exclude_main\"] = cluster_df[\"outlier_iforest\"]\n",
    "\n",
    "X_clust = X.loc[cluster_df[\"exclude_main\"].eq(0).to_numpy()]\n",
    "ids_clust = X_clust.index.to_numpy()\n",
    "\n",
    "display(cluster_df[\"exclude_main\"].value_counts())\n",
    "display(X_clust.shape)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "a68994e4-ddb6-44d4-b5a6-43a987da19ee",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The choice of removing 8% of outliers was motivated by the initial diagnostics from the \"exploratory k-means\" part. At the 5% of outliers mark, k-means was getting stuck at the 2-cluster solution, where one cluster was very small and consisted entirely of outliers; for k > 2 solutions, silhouette width was getting very poor. 8% is therefore the smallest number of outliers removed where k-means stopped merging all outliers in the same cluster and silhouette width diagnostics improved substantially. "
   ]
  },
