  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "bae5bac7-52a1-408a-8de6-faf054b2644c",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "**Cluster 1: exposed to mild rains and relatively resilient**\n",
    "\n",
    "From the profiles, cluster 1 seems to have the weakest rain-day penalty effect as the average rain_coef is almost zero, which means that the mere rain presence is not associated with a big drop of cyclists. On the other hand, precip_coef is negative, so bigger quantities of rain still reduce cyclists. For this cluster, rain_share is also much higher than that of other clusters; heavy_rain_share is lower. \n",
    "\n",
    "Overall, sites in this cluster seem to have many mildly rainy days but not necessarily heavy ones. Cyclist tolerate ordinary rain relatively well in this cluster, but the amount of rainfall can make it uncomfortable. \n",
    "\n",
    "(Note: this cluster has the highest nearest_station_km value, which might have affected its contents)\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "**Cluster 2: high-volume and resilient, commute-like**\n",
    "\n",
    "The second cluster has the biggest typical cycling volume and the most negative weekend coefficient, which means that sites in this cluster are likely used for commute purposes. Weather sensitivity also looks mild: precip_coef is the least negative and temp_coef is the lowest in this cluster, meaning that it is less dependent on nice weather and less strongly reduced by the rainfall amounts.\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "**Cluster 3: low-volume and fairly sensitive**\n",
    "\n",
    "Cluster 3 appears to be the most sensitive to weather: rain_coef and precip_coef are the most negative, meaning that cyclists use these sites less when it rains or when rainfall amount increases. temp_coef is the highest, which means that this cluster is used more on warmer days, and weekend_coef is less negative than in Cluster 2. \n",
    "\n",
    "Substantially, this cluster seems to consist of sites with more leisurely, weather-sensitive nature. \n"
   ]
  },
